  "prompt": "What is the candela? What is it used for?",
  "response": "The candela is the base unit of luminous intensity in the International System of Units (SI). It is defined as the luminous intensity, in a given direction, of a source that emits monochromatic radiation of frequency 540\u00d710\u00b9\u00b2 hertz and that has a radiant intensity in that direction of 1/683 watt per steradian.\n\nThe candela is used to measure the amount of light emitted by a light source in a specific direction. This is important in various fields such as lighting design, where it helps to determine the brightness and distribution of light in a space. It is also used in photometry, the science of measuring light, and in applications such as traffic signaling, stage lighting, and display technology.",
